{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Bishop v. Aronov |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate=March 15, |DecideYear=1991 |FullName=Phillip A. Bishop v. Aaron M. Aronov, Winton M. Blount, O.H. Delchamps, Jr., Sandrall Hullett, Guy Hunt, William Henry Mitchell, John T. Oliver, Jr., Thomas E. Rast, Yetta G. Samford, Jr., Martha H. Simms, Wayne Teague, Cleophus Thomas, Jr., George S. Shirley, Cordell Wynn, all in their official capacities as members of the Board of Trustees of the [[University of Alabama]] |Citations=926 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/926/1066/258472/ 1066]; 59 U.S.L.W. 2583; 65 Ed. Law Rep. 1109 |Prior=[[United States District Court for the Northern District of Alabama|District Court]] ruled in favor of Bishop |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[Emmett Ripley Cox]], [[Stanley F. Birch, Jr.]], [[Floyd R. Gibson]] |Majority=Gibson |JoinMajority= |Concurrence= |JoinConcurrence= |Dissent= |JoinDissent= |LawsApplied= |keywords= }}
'''''Bishop v. Aronov''''', 926 [[F.2d]] 1066 (11th Cir. 1991),<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Bishop v. Aronov |vol=926 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=1066 |pinpoint= |court=11th Cir. |date=1991 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/926/1066/258472/ |accessdate=2017-12-26 |quote=}} {{usgovpd}}</ref> was a 1991 legal case in which Phillip A. Bishop, an [[exercise physiology]] professor at the [[University of Alabama]], sued the college on [[free speech]] and [[academic freedom]] grounds, when it instructed him not to teach "[[intelligent design theory]]" in an extracurricular class and not to lecture on "evidences of God in Human Physiology" in class. The [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Alabama|District Court for the Northern District of Alabama]] found in favor of Bishop but the university appealed and the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] found that the classroom, during instructional time, was not an open forum, and that the university had a right to set the curriculum.<ref>''The Law of Higher Education'', William A. Kaplin, Barbara A. Lee, pp 262-263</ref><ref>[http://ncseweb.org/creationism/general/creationism-ideology-science Creationism, Ideology, and Science], [[Eugenie C. Scott]], [[New York Academy of Sciences]]. Published as ''The Flight From Reason.'' Volume 775 of the Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences. June 24, 1996.</ref>
A similar case was ''[[Edwards v. California University of Pennsylvania]]'' (3d Cir. 1998).<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Edwards v. California University of Pennsylvania |vol=156 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=488 |pinpoint= |court=3d Cir. |date=1998 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/156/488/481543/ |accessdate=2017-12-26 |quote=}}</ref>{{clear}}
